player.seasonOutlook: Philips was selected by the Titans in the fifth round of April's draft. He is a small, slot receiver and punt returner. He aligned inside on a class-high 91% of his career routes and his 7.33 aDOT was third lowest in this rookie class. The short-area role led to huge target shares (30% each of the last two seasons), but not much yardage efficiency (career 7.2 YPT). Philips' lack of speed is a concern, as he posted a 4.58 40-yard dash at 189 pounds at the combine (86 speed score). He'll look to make the cut as a standout punt returner and slot man.

The 2021 season was essentially a redshirt year for Atwell. A surprising second-round pick, Atwell was held without a single target on 10 offensive snaps and did most of his work on special teams (15 returns) . The Louisville product is one of the tiniest players in the league at 5-foot-9, 165 pounds. He's a terrific athlete with outstanding speed, elusiveness and big-play ability, but he isn't going to handle contested situations very well at his size. Atwell was primarily a slot target (92%) in college and may be limited to a gadget/situational deep-threat role in the pros. Atwell is behind Cooper Kupp, Allen Robinson II and Van Jefferson on the L.A. depth chart, so he has a ways to go for fantasy value. He's best as a dynasty stash.

Reynolds re-signed with Detroit after showing well in a brief stint with the team late last season. Reynolds opened 2021 with Tennessee, but was cut after five games and latched on with the Lions. That meant reuniting with Jared Goff, who was his QB when both were with the Rams during the 2017-20 seasons. Of course, Reynolds never quite emerged as a fantasy option with the Rams and that was true again last season. Despite playing 79% of the snaps during his time with the team, Reynolds was outside the top 50 in fantasy PPG and remains without a top-60 fantasy campaign for his career. The 27-year-old won't play as much this season after Detroit signed DJ Chark Jr. and drafted Jameson Williams as running mates for Amon-Ra St. Brown. Reynolds should not be on your draft radar.

Schwartz is entering his second NFL season after being limited to 23 targets in 14 games as a rookie. The third-round pick's minimal playing time was far from a surprise considering his extreme youth (he turned 21 just days prior to his first game). The speedster was utilized as an occasional deep threat (massive 16.8 average depth of target), which rarely worked (10 catches on 23 targets). The 2021 season was an obvious development year for Schwartz and he's positioned for a bigger workload in Cleveland's offense. Only Amari Cooper is clearly ahead of him on the depth chart, so a breakout is attainable. Consider him with a late pick in deep leagues.

Austin was selected by Pittsburgh in the fourth round of April's draft. He is an extremely undersized prospect, checking in as the shortest (5-foot-8) and lightest (170 pounds) receiver at the combine. Despite the small frame, Austin was heavily utilized at Memphis, posting receiving lines of 63-1,053-11 and 74-1,149-8 over the last two seasons. He handled a 29% target share both seasons and scored 27 touchdowns in his collegiate career. He showed well at the combine, finishing top five in the class in the 40, vertical and broad while posting the top short shuttle time (4.07). Austin will compete with fellow rookie George Pickens for work behind Diontae Johnson and Chase Claypool. He's only worth drafting in dynasty.

Shenault entered the 2021 season seemingly in perfect position for a breakout, but to say it didn't work out would be a major understatement. After producing 691 yards and five TDs on 76 touches as a rookie in 2020, Shenault fell to 660 yards and zero scores on 74 touches in 2021. He has been limited to short-area work (his 5.8 aDOT is second lowest among WRs during his two seasons) and hasn't had much work near the goal line (eight career end zone targets). Shenault also struggled with drops last season (second in the league with eight) and now has substantially more competition for targets with Christian Kirk, Zay Jones and Evan Engram added to the roster. Shenault is only 23 years old, but fantasy relevance in 2022 appears to be a long shot.

Thornton was selected by New England in the second round of April's draft. The Baylor product is a 6-foot-2, 181-pound vertical receiver with small hands but a huge wingspan whose game is built around speed (class-best 4.28 40-yard dash) and separation. He made a big leap in 2021 with a 62-948-10 receiving line on 102 targets, handling a 29% target share and massive 47% air-yard share. He worked from the perimeter on a class-high 92% of his routes and posted a 14.9 aDOT. New England has some respectable depth at receiver with DeVante Parker, Jakobi Meyers, Kendrick Bourne and Nelson Agholor, so Thornton may have a tough time finding snaps in his first season. He'll only be a late-round pick in 2022, though his dynasty value is intriguing after Mac Jones' successful rookie season.

Woods was selected by the Colts in the third round of April's draft. He is a super athlete with a massive frame (6-foot-7) and the biggest wingspan (82 inches) in the rookie TE class. He primarily blocked and was a non-factor in the pass game during three seasons at Oklahoma State (31-361-4 receiving line in 33 games) before busting out with a 44-598-8 line in 11 games at Virginia in 2021. Utilized as a vertical threat by the Cavaliers, Woods' 10.7 aDOT was third-highest in this class last season. His size, speed (4.61 40-yard dash), strength (class-high 24 bench reps) and 2021 breakout make him a very interesting dynasty stash, but don't expect much early-career fantasy production behind Mo Alie-Cox and Kylen Granson.

Carolina selected Marshall in the second round of the 2021 draft and immediately inserted him as its primary slot man. It didn't go well. Marshall turned 20 targets into 107 yards during his first five games and then was demoted behind journeyman Brandon Zylstra. Marshall managed only 31 yards on 11 targets the rest of the season. Of course, slow starts aren't a deal-breaker for rookies, and Marshall entered the league at an extremely young age (he turned 21 two months before his debut). The 6-foot-3 LSU product will again open 2022 behind DJ Moore and Robby Anderson with an opportunity to lock down slot duties. The 22-year-old is a post-hype sleeper.
